fitted values = predicted values lm(response \(\sim\) expression) corresponds to a linear model: response = \(\beta_0\) + \(\beta_1\)expression + \(\epsilon\): \[ \begin{pmatrix} y1 \\ y2 \\ y3 \\ . \\ . \\ . \\ y_n \\ \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & x_{11} \\ 1 & x_{21} \\ 1 & x_{31} \\ . \\ . \\ . \\ 1 & x_{n1} \\ \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} \beta_1 \\ \beta_2 \\ \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} \epsilon_1 \\ \epsilon_2 \\ \epsilon_3 \\ . \\ . \\ . \\ \epsilon_n \\ \end{pmatrix} \]

ANOVA test gives you: \(\sum{(y_i\ -\ \bar{y})^2}\ =\ \sum{(y_i\ -\ \hat{y_i})^2}\ +\ \sum{(\hat{y_i}\ -\ \bar{y})^2}\). Below test outputs RSS = 317.16, Regss = 808.89, and TSS = 808.89 + 317.76. As explanatory variables go up, RSS goes down (as \(R^2\) goes up), and Regss goes up. Tss stays the same although the number of explanatory variable changes. So, it is about changes between RSS and Regss.

reg_anova <- anova(reg1)

Although this works, computationally it is not the best way to compute b. Why? Because it is inefficient and be very inaccurate when the predictors are strongly correlated.

Always include intercept term!!!

int <- rep(1, nrow(reg1$model))

x <- cbind(int, reg1$model[,2])
y <- reg1$model[,1]

solve(t(x) %*% x) %*% t(x) %*% y
##            [,1]
## int 29.59985476
##     -0.04121512
solve(crossprod(x, x), crossprod(x,y))
##            [,1]
## int 29.59985476
##     -0.04121512
coef <- reg1$coefficients
coef
## (Intercept)        disp 
## 29.59985476 -0.04121512

\[y\ =\ X\hat{\beta}\ =\ (QR)\hat{\beta}\], so, \[\hat{\beta}\ =\ (QR)^{-1}y\ =\ R^{-1}Q^{-1}y\ =\ R^{-1}Q^Ty,\ as\ Q^TQ\ =\ I\]. And, to be unique, this works only if X is linerly independent meaning that X has full rank, and this is the same as betas least square estimator.

#Q. what is QR$qr??? 

QR <- qr(x) #same as reg1$qr

Q <- qr.Q(QR)
R <- qr.R(QR)

backsolve(R, crossprod(Q, y))
##             [,1]
## [1,] 29.59985476
## [2,] -0.04121512
forwardsolve(R, crossprod(Q, y))
##             [,1]
## [1,] 20.09062500
## [2,] -0.04121512
solve(R, crossprod(Q, y))
##            [,1]
## int 29.59985476
##     -0.04121512
